# ====================================================================
# FILAHA — AGENT RULES (Backend + Frontend)
# ====================================================================

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# STEP 1: READ BEFORE YOU CODE (MANDATORY)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# Before making ANY changes, read these two files IN ORDER:
#
# 1. PROJECT_CONTEXT.txt  → Master document: project description,
#    tech stack, ethical pillars, language rules, complete feature
#    list (Sections 6A–6J), DB schema (12 tables), AI response
#    contract, multi-country price sources, folder structure, and
#    current status log.
#    ALSO check "SECTION 14: CURRENT STATUS" at the bottom — it
#    tells you where the project currently stands and what was
#    last changed.
#
# 2. WALKTHROUGH.md       → Full system workflow, folder-by-folder
#    build order (Phase 0-9), data flows for MAÏ and SILA,
#    how to run/test each script, and the request lifecycle.
#    Use this to understand which phase you are in and what
#    comes next.
#
# Together these files give you the full picture. Do NOT start
# coding until you understand the current project state.

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# STEP 2: CODING RULES
# ------------------------------------------------------------------

# --- LANGUAGE & TEXT ---
# - Default UI language: Arabic (MSA / العربية الفصحى). No Darija.
# - Code language (variables, comments, file names, SQL names): English ONLY.
# - i18n keys: English snake_case. Values: target language.
# - RTL layout for Arabic. LTR for French/English.

# --- AI & ETHICS (NON-NEGOTIABLE) ---
# - Every AI recommendation MUST return the strict JSON contract:
#     { recommendation, explanation, confidence, factors[], action_items[], data_sources_used[] }
#   (See PROJECT_CONTEXT.txt Section 9).
# - Every AI recommendation MUST be logged to ai_explanations table.
# - Every AI decision, consent change, and data export MUST be logged
#   to data_audit_log table.
# - ALWAYS check data_sharing_consent before using farm data for
#   aggregates or AI training.
# - ALWAYS include an ExplainabilityPanel component alongside any
#   AI result in the frontend.

# --- MULTI-COUNTRY ARCHITECTURE ---
# - NEVER hardcode Morocco-specific logic.
# - ALWAYS use constants.js (ACTIVE_COUNTRIES, PRICE_SOURCES, CLIMATE_ZONES).
# - ALWAYS pass country_code where relevant (routes, services, DB queries).
# - Crop coefficients, price sources, and notifications are country-aware.

# --- EXTERNAL APIs ---
# - Weather: Open-Meteo (free, no key). Wrap in try/catch with fallback.
# - AI: Anthropic Claude 3.5 Haiku (primary). OpenRouter Gemma 4 (backup).
# - WhatsApp: AiSensy Cloud API (primary). Twilio SMS (fallback).
# - ALWAYS validate Claude JSON responses (strip markdown fences,
#   check required keys, validate confidence is 0.0–1.0).
# - ALWAYS handle API failures gracefully — never crash the server.

# --- FILE & FOLDER HYGIENE ---
# - Every file contains a top comment explaining what the file does.
# - Every folder has a "whatFor.txt" explaining its role.
# - Follow the build order in WALKTHROUGH.md — do not skip phases.
# - Keep code comments short and simple. No walls of text.
# - Use async/await. No callback hell.

# --- DATABASE ---
# - 12 tables: users, farms, countries, regions, crop_coefficients,
#   irrigation_logs, price_history, listings, offers, detections,
#   community_alerts, ai_explanations, data_audit_log.
# - All names in English. Add comments in English.
# - Use UUID primary keys. Use foreign keys with ON DELETE behavior.
# - Geo columns use GEOGRAPHY type for spatial queries.

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# STEP 3: COMMUNICATION RULES (WHEN WRITING CODE)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# When writing production code (not test scripts), you MUST:
#
#   1. Explain in the chat what the file does and why it exists.
#   2. Keep code comments short — easy for a beginner to understand.
#   3. After writing the code, tell the user IN THE CHAT (not in
#      file comments) exactly:
#        - How to test it (PowerShell commands)
#        - What output to expect
#        - What .env variables are needed
#   4. If you create a new table or modify schema, provide the SQL
#      and tell the user to run it in Supabase SQL Editor.
#
# This way the user learns while building.

# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# STEP 4: UPDATE PROJECT STATUS (MANDATORY — WHEN DONE)
# ------------------------------------------------------------------
# When you finish your session, you MUST update "SECTION 14: CURRENT
# STATUS" at the bottom of PROJECT_CONTEXT.txt. Add a new entry with:
#
#   ### [DATE] — [SHORT TITLE]
#   - **Phase:** Which phase (0-9) the project is at now
#   - **What was done:** Bullet list of files created/modified
#   - **What works now:** What can be tested/run after your changes
#   - **Next step:** What the next agent should work on
#
# This is how the next agent (or human) knows exactly where you
# stopped and what to do next. NEVER skip this step.